HEADWORD: Thorpe
<hw>Thorpe</hw>}</mhw> <pr>(th⟦ocir⟧rp)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧orp</ets>; akin to OS. & OFries.
<ets>thorp</ets>, D. <ets>dorp</ets>, G. <ets>dorf</ets>, Icel.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧orp</ets>, Dan. <ets>torp</ets>, Sw. <ets>torp</ets> a
cottage, a little farm, Goth. <ets>⟦thorn⟧a⟦uacute⟧rp</ets> a field, and
probably to Lith. <ets>troba</ets> a building, a house, W.
<ets>tref</ets> a hamlet, Ir. <ets>treabh</ets> a farmed village, a
tribe, clan, Gael. <ets>treabhair</ets> houses, and perhaps to L.
<ets>turba</ets> a crowd, mult. Cf. <er>Dorp</er>.]</ety> <def>A group
of houses in the country; a small village; a hamlet; a dorp; -- now
chiefly occurring in names of places and persons; <as>as,
Al<ex>thorp</ex>, Mable<ex>thorpe</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Within a
little <xex>thorp</xex> I staid.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Fairfax.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then <qex>thorpe</qex> and byre arose in fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

